{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8ba3bdb0-f9d9-47a9-9cf6-c2d0fa144f56","content":"In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:\n\n```csharp\npublic partial class App : Application\n{\n    public App()\n    {\n        InitializeComponent();\n    }\n\n    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n    {\n        var window = new Window(new AppShell());\n\n        window.Created   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Created\");\n        window.Activated += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Activated\");\n        window.Deactivated += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Deactivated\");\n        window.Stopped   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Stopped\");\n        window.Resumed   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Resumed\");\n        window.Destroying += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Destroying\");\n\n        // Visibility events (desktop platforms)\n        window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Backgrounding\");\n\n        return window;\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Event order on launch:** `Created` → `Activated`\n**App backgrounded:** `Deactivated` → `Stopped`\n**App foregrounded:** `Resumed` → `Activated`\n**App closed:** `Destroying`\n\n> **Tip:** `Backgrounding` fires on iOS/macOS when the app enters the background and lets you persist state via `BackgroundingEventArgs.State`. Use `Resumed` to restore it.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3b67fece-e50c-4a37-8ff0-3d903a3e8034","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI Window lifecycle events and how to subscribe to them for logging/debugging. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI development - I can answer it directly without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":443,"requestId":"3C27:B0194:D37DB1:107B340:6A0129B7"},"id":"fe296058-d791-47b9-9327-76f9d988e225","timestamp":"2026-05-11T00:58:39.847Z","parentId":"652b7ed9-4a5c-43a3-a63d-b12754dce1e8"}
